an Air Superiority Fighter (which it no longer is).  <br>
So is the F-16 (which is a superior dog fighter compared to the F-15).<br>
<br>
Current production of the F-22 is irrelevant as it is still undergoing<br>
prototype testing, eventual orders will be in the hundreds and<br>
will replace the aging F-15 in the Air Superiority role.<br>
<br>
Your quote says F-14, F-14 F-14, yet you wrap it up by saying F-15...<br>
You do understand that the F-14 is a Naval aircraft, and the F-15<br>
is an Air Force Fighter... two completely different planes.  Anyway,<br>
the current revs of the F-18 are superior in the ground attack role compared<br>
to the F-14, it wsa a wise decision.  If Grumman wanted to survive<br>
in a capatilist environment then maybe they should have concentrated<br>
on R&amp;D a little more instead of assuming they would continue to<br>
receive government handouts.<br>
<br>
Your statement that the JSF is not getting anywhere is based on what?<br>
They have already produced several prototype variants which are <br>
undergoing flight testing.  One of which is a VTOL replacement for<br>
the aging Harrier.  Plans are to order somewhere in the range of <br>
3,000 Joint Strike Fighter variants between 2005-30.<br>
<br>
That's a LOT of aircraft!  So much for your theory that the defense<br>
industry is dead!<br>
<br>
You must understand that new programs take time, and that these aircraft<br>
will eventually replace the junk in our existing inventory.<br>
<br>
The F-14, F-15, F-16 all date back to the late 60's to mid 70's.<br>
Old Stuff that needs to be replaced ASAP.<br>
<br>
The F-22 and the JSF are just around the corner.<br>
